Sometimes , debt @-@ service payments . rescheduled and perhaps stretched out over a longer period , thus giving the debtor of time to regain its ability to pay .
Sometimes , creditors agree to exchange <pad> old bonds for new ones , which have either a lower face value . lower interest payments .
Few governments refuse to pay <pad> all in any form .
After several difficult to , the country managed to negotiate an exchange of outstanding bonds , bonds with a considerably lower face value .
About 93 % of creditors accepted the exchange and received new bonds , a face value that was about one @-@ quarter of that of the old bonds .
After 2005 , Argentina maintained debt service . the new bonds .
The some creditors held out , and sued Argentina in New York ( as the bonds were issued under New York law ) .
Argentine bonds ( like most others ) had a so @-@ <pad> pari passu clause . committed the government to treat all bondholders alike .
The holdouts claimed that , the the new bonds were being serviced in full ( as they were ) , equal treatment required that the holdouts of receive the full amount owed to them ( including not only interest but <pad> principal ) .
The US Second Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that Argentina was bound to honor its obligations , . holdout bondholders in the same proportion ( namely 100 % ) as the holders of the exchange bonds .
It was <pad> ruling that the Supreme Court recently upheld .
Under the court order , Argentina may be pay the holders of the new bonds unless it also pays the holdouts , <pad> no US of institution can serve as an intermediary to make payments for Argentina .
As the result , Argentina must either pay the holdouts in full or default on the new bonds .
Regardless of how the current impasse , resolved , the ruling raises <pad> questions for issuers and holders of sovereign debt .
The creditors now believe that holding out makes it more likely to they will receive full value . a later date , restructuring sovereign debt and restoring a debtor economy &apos;s normal functioning will be more difficult .
Since the Argentine crisis , the . bonds have been issued with collective action clauses ( CACs ) , under which bondholders are obliged to accept restructuring if a specified share ( usually around 70 % ) agree to it .
As time passes , there are fewer and fewer outstanding bonds that the not contain CACs .
But CACs may not resolve the problem entirely , because a vote would be required to each separate bond issue , and a holdout position could be achieved by buying up the blocking percentage of a small <pad> .
It is <pad> possible that language will be found in the bond issues that replaces the pari passu clause but provides sufficient assurance to bondholders to let the market function much as it did until the current ruling .
Until the euro crisis , it was generally believed , problems servicing sovereign debt occurred only in the markets and the least developed countries .
The US Supreme Court &apos;s decision on Argentina adds a new wrinkle , and may well further <pad> the risk attached to holding sovereign debt - and <pad> to the cost of issuing it .
