WASHINGTON , DC - Since the start of his <pad> administration , US President Barack Obama has repeated a simple mantra concerning other countries : &quot; With power comes responsibility . &quot; </s> has demonstrated repeatedly that it understands and accepts this responsibility ; Germany may now be following suit .
Several weeks ago , German President Joachim Gauck &apos;s opening address to the 50th annual Munich Security Conference reflected on the Federal Republic of evolution over those five decades , a period that gave rise to &quot; a good Germany , the <pad> of have ever known . &quot;
And , because Germany benefits more than most <pad> from the current open , value @-@ based . . , it has , Gauck said , a greater responsibility to defend and extend that order .
Gauck &apos;s speech reflected the thinking in the important new report , entitled New Power , New Responsibility , released by the Stiftung Wissenschaft und Politik and the German Marshall Fund , the United States .
The report - the product of several months of debate within the German foreign @-@ policy and security community - identifies Germany &apos;s current values and interests as a commitment to &quot; human dignity , freedom , democracy , the rule of law , and to an international order that is based on universal norms . &quot; As Gauck proclaimed , Germany &apos;s &quot; overriding strategic objective &quot; must be the &quot; preservation and continued adaptation &quot; of this <pad> .
To achieve this objective , Germany , become a &quot; shaping power , &quot; a state with the ability to solve problems and resolve conflicts affecting all . part of the international community .
The traditional determinants of states &quot; power relative to other states - geography , demography , economic heft , and military @-@ , coupled with the availability of resources and technological proficiency - remain important ; but <pad> are often insufficient to confer actual influence in international politics .
A shaping power builds relationships and invests in institutions that allow the to work well with others and <pad> create and mobilize &quot; coalitions and networks of like @-@ minded states . &quot;
As a shaping power with an enormous stake in preserving and extending the openness of the international <pad> , Germany has a special responsibility to help integrate <pad> . powers into that system .
The has long sought a seat on the United Nations Security Council , making the cause with Japan , Brazil , and India .
But New Power , New Responsibility suggests a different path , arguing for the reform of the Security Council in a way . would merge the French and British seats into a permanent European seat in a &quot; slightly enlarged circle of permanent members , &quot; while the ensuring European representation among the non @-@ permanent <pad> .
Under this scenario , Germany would play a role in global peace . security through the European seat , as well to serving as a periodic rotating member .
Moreover , Germany recognizes the need to consolidate Europe </s> voting power and reduce the number of the seats in other global institutions , such as the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank , to make room for emerging powers .
This renewed commitment to . strong and united Europe is the second pillar of a twenty @-@ first @-@ century German foreign policy .
New Power , New Responsibility calls for &quot; deepening &quot; the European Union through measures that would include democratizing . financial decision @-@ making by directly engaging national parliamentarians . exchanging tighter European fiscal constraints on member @-@ &quot; budgets for a European banking union , a eurozone budget , and Eurobonds .
In foreign and security policy , New Power , New Responsibility proposes strengthening the role of the EU High Representative and the role of the European Action Service .
Current EU High Representative Catherine Ashton continues to prove the worth of EU foreign @-@ policy institutions , , for example , brokering a remarkable peace between Serbia and Kosovo , playing a key role in nuclear negotiations with Iran .
Gauck told Germans in no uncertain terms that they been to be willing to use force , at least as a last resort , and reproached those of his fellow citizens &quot; who use Germany , guilt for the past as a shield for laziness or a desire to disengage from the world . &quot;
More controversially , Gauck proclaimed the need to Security Council authorization of any use of force , but also hinted at a Kosovo precedent for possible . intervention in Syria .
