BERLIN - The world &apos;s task in addressing North Korea &apos;s saber rattling . made no easier to the fact that it confronts an impoverished and effectively defeated country .
On the contrary , it is in such circumstances that calm foresight . most necessary .
The genius of the Habsburg Empire &apos;s Prince Klemens von Metternich in framing a new international order after the Napoleonic Wars was <pad> he did not push a defeated France into a corner .
Although Metternich sought to deter any possible French resurgence , he restored France , prewar frontiers .
By contrast , as Henry Kissinger has argued , the victors in World War , could neither deter a defeated Germany nor provide it with incentives , accept the Versailles Treaty .
Instead , the imposed harsh terms , hoping to weaken Germany permanently .
During the Cuban missile crisis , he did not try to humiliate . win a total victory over the Soviet Union .
Rather , he put himself in Nikita Khrushchev . shoes and agreed to dismantle , secretly , American missiles in Turkey and Italy in exchange for withdrawal of Soviet missiles . Cuba .
Sadly , North Korea has not received the far @-@ sighted statesmanship .
Faced with the North &apos;s dangerous nuclear game , we should ask what would have happened if , over <pad> last 20 some @-@ , the North Korea , had been approached with the sagacity of Metternich and Kennedy .
Of course , North Korea is <pad> early @-@ nineteenth century France or the USSR of 1962 .
In the eyes of the ( including Japanese ) political leaders , it has never amounted to more than a small , fringe country whose economic failings made it appear to be poised perpetually on the edge of self @-@ destruction .
For the most <pad> , world , preferred not to be bothered with North Korea , and so reacted in an ad hoc way whenever it created a security problem .
But now , following the North &apos;s <pad> nuclear tests , and <pad> its improving ballistic @-@ missile capabilities , that approach is no longer tenable .
Perhaps the best chance to address the problem at the earlier stage . immediately after the Soviet Union &apos;s collapse in 1991 .
Back then , Kim Il @-@ sung - the North &apos;s founder - faced economic collapse , diminution . his conventional military forces , and diplomatic isolation .
In interviews with Asahi Shimbun and The Washington Times in March <pad> April 1992 , Kim clearly expressed a wish to establish diplomatic relations with the <pad> .
But US and South Korean <pad> were not ready to accommodate Kim &apos;s overture .
Their received ideas about the Korea prevented them from recognizing a fast @-@ changing political reality .
If North Korea had reciprocated in the timely manner following US envoy William Perry &apos;s visit to Pyongyang in May 1999 , President Bill Clinton &apos;s policy of engagement with the North might have been upgraded . a push for normalization . diplomatic relations .
Instead , the North procrastinated , sending Vice Marshall Jo Myong @-@ rok of the US only in October 2000 , near the end of Clinton &apos;s presidency .
A few months later , newly elected President George W. the reversed Clinton &apos;s North Korea policy .
The still recall the difficulty that I faced , as South Korea &apos;s foreign minister , <pad> convincing Bush administration policymakers to negotiate with North Korea instead of merely applying pressure and waiting for the North to capitulate .
Back then , North Korea was restarting its Yongbyon nuclear facility and producing plutonium , thus strengthening its bargaining position vis @-@ à @-@ vis the <pad> .
Precious time was squandered . North Korea &apos;s first nuclear test in 2006 .
Though Bush shifted his policy toward bilateral negotiations with the North a few months later , the Kim regime had to much more obstinate .
Indeed , North Korea , behavior has since become even more volatile .
Its sinking of the South Korean corvette Cheonan . the shelling of Yeonpyeong Island . 2010 were unprecedented , and raised inter @-@ Korean tensions to their highest level in decades .
Today , following the North &apos;s third nuclear test , we seem to have entered the most precarious stage yet , with the regime declaring that it will never surrender its nuclear option .
The first option should be deterrence of the aggression through diplomacy .
The achieving diplomatic deterrence will depend on China &apos;s cooperation , the this requires that China &apos;s vital national @-@ security interests be recognized .
China fears not only the social and economic consequences of a North Korean implosion , but also the strategic consequences of reunification - in particular , that the US of , through the alliance with South Korea , would gain access to territory <pad> its border .
A mere statement by the US of it has no intention to press the military advantage will not assuage China &apos;s fears .
The leaders recall that the US promised Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev , German reunification and democratic transition in Eastern Europe would not mean eastward expansion of NATO .
The a more concrete undertaking , one that preserves South Korea &apos;s bedrock security concerns , is needed .
Only after its security is assured will China free itself from complicity in North Korean brinkmanship . be better able to control the North <pad> behavior . &amp; # 160 ;
But Chinese cooperation , though necessary , <pad> not resolve the North Korea problem , its own .
A comprehensive approach , recognize the speed of internal change , especially in the minds of ordinary North Koreans .
Simply put , North Koreans are not as isolated as the once were , the have a growing appreciation of their impoverishment , owing primarily to greater trade @-@ closer connections with booming China .
This internal change needs to be encouraged , because the will prove <pad> effective than external pressure in influencing the regime &apos;s behavior .
The such encouragement must be undertaken in ways that do not incite the North &apos;s fears of being destroyed by indirect means . &amp; # 160 ; South Korean <pad> Park Geun @-@ hye &apos;s recent proposal to provide humanitarian assistance despite the recent spike in tension , is a start in the <pad> direction .
The lives . ordinary <pad> Koreans matter as much as the security of North Korea &apos;s neighbors .
A comprehensive approach is required - one that focuses . much on the human dimension as on the <pad> dimension .
It remains to be seen . this <pad> requires more foresight and courage than today &apos;s political leaders in South Korea , the West , and China can muster .
The deaths of Yasir Arafat and of Sheikh Zayd , the long @-@ standing ruler , the United Arab Emirates , continues the generational change that began in 1999 @-@ 2000 , when the leaders of Jordan , Morocco , Bahrain , and Syria died . quick succession .
Across the Middle East people are younger , and <pad> political leaders older , the the world average .
The gradual replacement . . generation of elites by another may be one of the key factors in determining whether or not effective <pad> takes place in the Arab world .
At present , four political generations co @-@ exist . the region &apos;s socio @-@ political map .
The outgoing leadership generation - that of Arafat , King Hussein , Hafiz al @-@ Assad , King Fahd and President Mubarak - was born before 1935 and has determined events in the <pad> East since the 1970 &quot; s .
The leaders came of age and began their careers during the era of decolonization .
They been weaned on Gamal Abdel @-@ Nasser &apos;s pan @-@ Arab nationalism , and the crucial political event for them was the <pad> defeat in the 1967 Arab @-@ Israeli war .
Members of this generation sought a <pad> Arab leadership that <pad> create a balance of power with Israel .
The also believed in - or at least toyed with - forms of socialism , étatism , and did not consider democracy or civil rights to be priorities .
The <pad> generation was born between 1935 and 1955 , and in many respects represents a generation &quot; . between . &quot;
Most benefited . the economic growth and expanded educational opportunities associated with the oil boom , the 1970 &quot; s .
At the <pad> time , political participation remained blocked by the previous generation , which , intended to give up power voluntarily .
Unsurprisingly , many in this generation grew dissatisfied , the not a few began to look <pad> Islamic alternatives to the prevailing political systems .
Rather than determining events in the coming two or three decades , this generation is likely to be sidelined by the next cohort , born between 1955 . 1975 .
This . the generation of Syria &apos;s President Bashar al @-@ Assad , Jordan &apos;s King Abdullah and Morocco &apos;s King Muhammad VI . Some call this the &quot; generation of sons &quot; - sons of leaders who led their states for decades .
This age cohort was not much influenced by the Arab @-@ Israeli wars . the East @-@ West conflict . Instead , their <pad> education included the Gulf War of 1991 and the Arab @-@ Israeli peace process of the 1990 &quot; s , with its crises and breakdown .
Jailed West Bank Fatah leader Marwan Barghouti is as representative of this group of . leaders of Syria and Jordan .
Members of this generation are <pad> acquainted with notions of globalization and economic reform than with socialism , revolution .
Except for the Palestinians , they have never known their countries other than the independent and comparatively stable states .
In the Palestinian territories , the jil al @-@ intifada , the generation of the ( first and second ) Palestinian uprising , will be <pad> the founding generation .
But it is the fourth group that underscores the relevance of generational issues in the . world .
The when combined , the first three generations make up barely one @-@ third @-@ the entire Arab population .
Almost 60 % of all Arabs . younger than 20 , with roughly 70 % below the age of 30 .
This raises a key question : what happens to these Arab &quot; baby boomers &quot; . the generation now coming to power clings to it the tenaciously as the generation of Mubarak , Assad , and Hussein ?
The political generation of Bashar al @-@ Assad , King Abdullah , and Gamal Mubarak - son . Egypt &apos;s ailing president - forms a less coherent picture of that of the outgoing leadership .
In that elder generation , the had pursued military careers , and many of the aides and collaborators were engineers and civil servants .
The socio @-@ professional profile . the new elite is broader .
Economists , bankers , and entrepreneurs as well as of technology . communication experts are common .
There are <pad> . traditional politicians : personalities who see themselves as representatives of particular social or economic interests , not as apolitical technocrats .
This . leadership elite is in many ways , cosmopolitan than its predecessors ; their average level of education is higher ; a few have foreign degrees .
Developments , Morocco , Bahrain , and Jordan certainly seem to suggest that this changing of the guard can help soften rigid political structures and allow for broader participation .
But generational change need to be accompanied by economic <pad> and steps towards political liberalization - witness North Korea under Kim Il Sung &apos;s son , Kim Jong Il .
Indeed , experience gives little reason , presume that a modern way . speaking , willingness to liberalize the economy , and an urge for technological development automatically translates into a democratic opening .
It , more realistic to expect <pad> the new Arab elites will make use of their <pad> &quot; authoritarian institutions , both to overcome resistance to their economic agendas and to consolidate their newly acquired power .
The is anything but a risk @-@ free path .
Without a significant increase in opportunities for the participation , including genuinely competitive elections , the chasm between a predominantly young population and a ruling elite with the narrow generational base will widen .
Such continuing political inertia leaves an <pad> young Arab population prey to the appeal of extremist ideologies , while driving the best and brightest to seek to fortune elsewhere .
The problem , succession in the Arab secular republics highlights their predicament in the transition to a post @-@ revolutionary phase , <pad> succession in regimes that fail to build strong institutions always risks triggering a systemic crisis .
The the decision by some in favor of dynastic succession may be lacking in the , it is not entirely devoid of merit .
Arguably , it is a choice for economic modernization , the an end to the politics of conflict , and for positive political change further down the road .
Years of Western @-@ backed repressive authoritarianism nipped in the bud any potential growth of the liberal alternative to the incumbent Arab regimes , and turned any abrupt move to free elections into <pad> dangerous exercise in Islamic democracy .
A democracy that produces governments led to Hamas , Hezbollah , or the Muslim Brotherhood is inevitably bound to be anti @-@ Western and opposed to an American @-@ inspired &quot; . process &quot; with the .
Syria has already sought to assure <pad> continuity through quasi @-@ monarchic hereditary succession with the move from Hafez al @-@ Assad to his son Bashar .
There are indications that Egypt might follow suit , the Hosni Mubarak &apos;s son , Gamal , taking over .
Likewise , Libya &apos;s Muammar Khaddafi may be succeeded by his son , Seif el Islam .
As products of revolutionary military takeovers , these secular nationalist regimes failed to produce genuine popular legitimacy . have had to fall . on the dynastic succession practiced by the regimes they toppled .
The centrality of hereditary succession in the quest for peace and stability was shown by Hafez al @-@ Assad when he agreed to unprecedented <pad> will gestures aimed at drawing Ehud Barak . Israeli government into a peace deal .
An old and sick man who was to die a few months later , he acted with a sense of urgency to reach the deal that would relieve his inexperienced son of the burden of struggling . the <pad> of the Golan Heights .
Bashar Assad remains essentially loyal to the father &apos;s legacy .
